ODE XVII.

Whilesoever, my Tyndaris, round and about us Ring the smooth sheeny lime-rocks of sloping Ustica, And the valleys embosomed below, With the sweet haunting pipe of the god.

Over me watch the gods with an aspect of favour, To the gods dear at heart are the muse and my worship. Here our rich rural honours shall flow From a brimmed cornucopia to thee.
